Fig\ref{fig:ee18btech11026_1} is a bode plot, plotted considering asymptotic approximations for better understanding. We can observe that due to a dominant pole at $f_{D}$ we will have a 0dB gain at $f_{p1}$, while earlier it used to be 80 dB , which could have lead to unstability.
\item{\textbf{Verification through bode plots:}}\\
Loop gain : L(s) \\
Closed Loop gain : $T(s) = \frac{G(s)}{1+L(s)}$

The stability of closed loop gain can be determined through the bode plots of its loop gain L(s)\\
\begin{align}
L(j\omega)=\abs{{G(j\omega)H(j\omega)}}e^{j\phi(\omega)}
\end{align}
Let $\omega_{180}$ be the frequency at which the phase of $L(j\omega)$ i.e; $\phi(w)$ = $-180^{\circ}$ and using it the stability of the system is determined as follows :
\begin{align}
\abs{{G(j\omega_{180})H(j\omega_{180})}} < 1 \implies Stable \\
\abs{{G(j\omega_{180})H(j\omega_{180})}} > 1 \implies Unstable 
\end{align}
For uncompensated System: 
$L_{1}(s) = G(s).1$\\
$w_{180} = w_{1}$\\
For Compensated System : 
$L_{2}(s) = G(s).H(s)$\\
$w_{180} = w_{2}$\\
The below are the Bode plots : 

\begin{figure}[!h]
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=\columnwidth]{./figs/ee18btech11026/ee18btech11026_2.eps}
    \caption{Bode Plots for verificaition}
    \label{fig:ee18btech11026_2}
\end{figure}

From the Fig\ref{fig:ee18btech11026_2} we can easily observe that : 
\begin{align}
\abs{L_{1}(jw_{1})} > 1
\end{align}
$\implies L_{1}$ is unstable.
\begin{align}
\abs{L_{2}(jw_{2})} < 1
\end{align}
$\implies L_{2}$ is stable.\\
Hence the designed Low pass network placed in negative feedback, compensates our open loop gain and stabilizes the closed loop gain of the overall system.
